{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b6270747-bbaf-40b6-95b0-17f48145496f","content":"Here's the analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe developer report confirms it: **MSBuild process startup + project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation is the bottleneck. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server process. Each CLI invocation pays JIT + restore + evaluation costs from scratch.\n\n## Recommendations (ordered by impact)\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop\nKeeps the build host alive and watches for changes — avoids startup overhead entirely:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Skip restore when packages haven't changed\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\nThis alone can save ~1s per invocation by skipping NuGet evaluation.\n\n### 3. Enable the MSBuild Server (`.NET 8+`)\nThis is the CLI equivalent of what VS does — reuses an MSBuild server process across builds:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nOr persist it in your shell profile. The first build is normal speed; subsequent builds reuse the warm server (JIT'd code, cached project graph).\n\n### 4. Combine flags for maximum effect\nFor one-off builds when not using `watch`:\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore -nodeReuse:true\n```\n\n### Summary\n\n| Approach | Startup Cost | Best For |\n|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet build` (default) | Full (~2-4s) | CI / one-off |\n| `dotnet build --no-restore` | Partial (~1-2s) | Quick one-off |\n| `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | Warm after 1st | Repeated CLI builds |\n| `dotnet watch build` | None after 1st | Edit-build-test loop ✅ |\n\n**For the dev inner loop, `dotnet watch build` is the best answer** — it mirrors how VS stays fast by keeping the process alive.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0ff81f83-58ee-4295-ae86-8d537c6d5763","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even with no changes), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've already verified analyzers aren't the issue and incremental build targets work correctly.\n\nThe key insight from the report is: \"The overhead seems to come from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\"\n\nThis is a well-known issue. Visual Studio keeps an MSBuild server process running in the background, which avoids the JIT and project re-evaluation overhead on each build. The CLI, by default, starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\n\nThe main fix is enabling the MSBuild server in .NET 8+, which you can activate via an environment variable to keep the MSBuild process alive between builds and eliminate the JIT and re-evaluation costs. For iterative development workflows, `dotnet watch` is another option that maintains the build process across multiple invocations. The MSBuild server feature in .NET 8 with the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable can keep processes alive between builds similar to Visual Studio. For the fastest iteration, I'd combine `dotnet watch build` for continuous rebuilds with the `--no-restore` flag to skip package restoration when dependencies haven't changed, which eliminates unnecessary overhead on subsequent builds.","outputTokens":1265,"requestId":"781C:36731D:117AC0:1599C7:69F54AA4"},"id":"55f270c7-feb0-4910-9e89-21f98d11933f","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:52:17.254Z","parentId":"d88126c6-11c6-43a7-a671-fbf740599ed6"}
